inate a joint rite between Lumin Weavers, Fathom Tongues, Brinewardens, and Tidemasons.\",\n        \"Place the Moonkey Setting Sketch and the Echo-Baffle Coil at designated resonance points around the Tide Looms.\",\n        \"Lead a calm procession around the Spine Market while maintaining order and light density.\",\n        \"Support Tern Quietwake at the Thalassarium lectern to produce a stabilizing chord without invoking the Long Note.\",\n        \"Negotiate a written accord for a neutral 'safe-cut' network and limits on unilateral flow changes.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Asha Heliope\", \"lines\": \"Kael, we ask the light to be a language tonight, not a weapon, and I trust your hand to keep its grammar true. The Loom halls will look like sleeping whales under our braids, and the glow will move as if a current were taught to walk; do not let any one strand surge or fade without the others heeding it. I have weighed the pride of guilds and the appetite of markets, and still I say that calm spectacle is a kind of courage when the city’s nerves are raw. Keep our lampers close but not clotted, keep our children in the warm center of the lines, and if fear rises, let it rise into the lantern glass and burn there until it learns to breathe. If someone tries to tilt this rite into procession or protest, you will be the hinge that quietly will not turn, and I will stand in your wake with all the glow Thassyl can weave.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Tern Quietwake\", \"lines\": \"I have listened to stones cough truth and to waves swallow whole lies, and I tell you this chord we carry will not bow to panic if we do not teach it the taste of panic first. We will stand at the whale-tooth lectern and hum a narrow bridge between waking and sleep, a careful strand of no and yes braided so fine even the tide must lean close to hear. Hold the Echo-Baffle Coil where the Looms cast their echoes back at themselves, and let those echoes slow and knead until the gears remember that haste is not strength. When you set the Moonkey sketch in its place, do not think of keys and gates; think of a map of breath laid upon a chest, and where you lay it, that breath will even. I ask your steadiness because steadiness is the only honest robe for power tonight, and I will read the city’s answer in how your shoulders do not rise when the hum thickens.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Oaric Bent\", \"lines\": \"I have seen water carry castles and I have seen ropes argue with their own fibers, and I will not yield my codes to a song or a pageant, not ever, not once. But I have also seen a gear stop chattering when a hand that did not own it touched it like a friend, and I will admit that teeth sometimes answer tone better than orders. If your lines run clean and my crews can keep their attention on bolts and not on banners, I will sign a safe-cut accord that says no one reaches for the sluice keys alone again. You will not hear me pray with the Children nor hum with the Tongues, but you will hear my keys turn only when daylight and witnesses agree, and you may write that down in whatever ink you like. Keep my apprentices out of speeches and out of stamp parades, and I will keep your routes from vanishing under the caprices of a single frightened morning.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Mara Vell-Seren\", \"lines\": \"You know me as coin and contract, Kael, and I will not pretend otherwise, because truth told well keeps better than lies lacquered with piety. If the rite lays a calm across the Looms, my divers return with lungs unburned by fear, my ledgers clean their smudges of disaster clauses, and my factors stop sharpening quills on other people’s grief. I will look at your accord with a merchant’s eye and a widow’s memory, and if it keeps the tide of tantrum from slapping the pearl row, I will pretend it was my idea and pay twice for the ink. Do not ask me to sing, but do not doubt that I can count heartbeats to a chorus, and I will stand where I must stand so your lanterns are not mistaken for a parade of demand. Bring me a city that hears itself like a crew at oars, and I will bid tariff clerks count in softer voices and teach my house to breathe with the hum.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Ysger Thorn\", \"lines\": \"We will ring the Spine with cutters at idle steam and boots at easy stance, and anyone who comes running with a spark in their mouth will find the rain we have trained for years to pour. Do not mistake our calm for indifference, nor our distance for disdain; it is a measured quiet that keeps people whole when rumors run like oil on stone. I will keep my wardens’ whistles down and their hands open, because that works better than pikes when children carry the light, but if a Gray Sail trick or a zealot’s shove turns the press, we will be the bales that keep the stack from falling. You left us, and I still called you when the whale-road went strange, because I trust your eyes and your pull more than I trust a written order in a wet wind. Do your part, Rimestrand, and I will do mine; neither of us needs to be forgiven tonight if both of us remember why we ever swore to stand between panic and people.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Tullis Nacrethane\", \"lines\": \"Some say the sea is a mother whose patience has been bribed with shells, but I say she is a judge who loves mercy, and mercy is a discipline before it is a feeling. I will knot oaths in brine so quick tongues tie themselves before they lash, and I will walk the sanctum’s orphans at the lantern-center because they know how to breathe to the count of a song. Do not melt the city’s ears with a forbidden note, and do not hammer the Looms into a false obedience; instead, let the rite remind the bones that a house can bow without breaking, and a tide can turn without drowning. If your accord writes respect into the margins where power loves to scrawl excuses, I will bless it with a low yes and a clean bowl of water, and I will ask my zealots to wash their hands before they touch any more shrines with fervor. Remember, Kael, that listening is a posture, not a surrender, and we will hold it with you until the last echo goes quiet.\"\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Walk the Circle of Light as a Promise, not a Protest. Let the glow move like a tide that remembers every shore and will not be rushed. Keep Children and elders at the center, Weavers at the rim, and widen the path whenever fear narrows it. Refuse banners, decline chants, and replace them with breathing counts and soft whistles that herd panic like sheep. Make the night a lesson in gentleness so solid that even skeptics feel foolish raising their voice above the hum.\", \"text\": \"Kael sets the pace as a librarian of light would catalogue calm, finger to lips, eyes moving ahead to where lanterns might snag in the bones and where shadows might twist into rumors. Instructions ripple down the line like tidy surf—three beats breathe, two beats step, eyes on the nearest glow, trust the warmth of the shoulder beside you—and the procession answers by becoming a body that remembers how to move. Children in nacre masks tuck small hands into net-mitts, and the Brinewardens uncoil a yard of distance so that no one feels pushed into running or into stubborn stillness. At each resonance post, Kael fits the Echo-Baffle Coil and the Moonkey sketch without flourish, as if setting down familiar tools in their proper drawers, and the Looms’ chatter slims into a patient click. On the final bend before the Thalassarium, Kael raises a palm instead of a shout, and the whole circle slows without jolting, like a crew of oars guided by a coxswain they trust more than the bank’s yelling.\", \"outcome\": \"The city sighs as if a cramp has eased, and the chord Tern hums lands on the Looms like a gull settling on a safe post. Oaric’s jaw loosens by a finger’s width and he nods once, the nod of a builder who recognizes a